##U.S. 'Three Musketeers' fight to save China

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

When the subject of human survival is wrapped up in viruses and pandemics, Donald Trump, the man in the White House, Antony Fossey, the man on the street, and Powell, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, are all playing the old game or the Ruyi Jingu Bang, we don't know yet

By Jin Yan, CAIJING correspondent, Washington

Editor | Susie

Sunday, March 15th. Cloudy and cold weather in Washington. On My facebook page, a lot of my friends are out photographing spring. Magnolias and Cherry blossoms bloom gracefully despite the gloomy skies and the ravages of the epidemic; many are retweeting the new realities of the epidemic: Some countries have closed their cities on Sunday, curfews and travel restrictions, europe, Denmark, Poland, the Czech Republic, closed its borders... the impossible became possible, and the government became more and more extreme.

On wechat, Feng Daxuan, a former vice president of the University of Texas at Dallas, left me a message in English.

'social unrest has started in the U.S. , ' he said. He was referring to social unrest in which people buy irrationally large quantities of rice, milk, toilet paper and other necessities. "My real fear is that when the number of confirmed cases reaches 500,000 -- The number of infected people in the United States could reach one million in three days, and two million in six days, according to the index model -- the country could face a serious political earthquake, " he said

Feng told me that when he was a physics major, he understood the profound and simple meaning of "exponential growth. ". His numbers didn't surprise me, however, after a few days earlier, U.S. media authorities reported that, according to internal documents, CDC model analyst Matthew Biggerstaff was on a conference call in February, about 50 teams of experts from around the world were briefed on the likely direction of the US outbreak. Biggerstaff used the model to calculate four outcomes based on the spread of the virus. One result is that between 160m and 214m people in the US are expected to be infected, and the epidemic could last a year. At worst, 1.7 million people in the United States will die from the disease. And bigstaff predicts that between 2.4 m and 21m Americans will need to be hospitalized.

But it was only when he told his story that the gravity of things began to sink in. He said he was in graduate school at the university during the Vietnam War. But for all the Anti War sentiment, American society felt far more stable than it does now, and he suspects that the current national mood of anxiety was not present during World War I or World War II. But there is no sign that Donald Trump understands the gravity of the situation.

Donald Trump is known to some Chinese Americans as the Grand Marshal. Donald Trump, sitting in the White House, is clearly the political commander in chief who will lead the American people out of the crisis by formulating a grand strategy. But Donald Trump's response to the virus has been widely criticized as opaque, politically charged and inefficient.

Following the formula of Hollywood blockbusters, when disaster strikes, American intellectuals will always jump out of books and laboratories to save the world, this time the folk saviour is Antony Fossey, national director of Allergy and Institute of Medical Science at the NIH.

The public health crisis has been accompanied by economic disaster. Federal Reserve Chairman Powell shook things up on the evening of March 15 when his Federal Reserve announced that it had cut its target range for the federal funds rate to an ultra low level of zero to 0.25 percent, it will also buy $700bn of treasury bonds and mortgage-backed securities. Is believed to have used the king's deep fryer.

When the subject of human survival is wrapped up in viruses and pandemics, it's not clear whether the three musketeers are old school or Ruyi Jingu Bang.

(as the global economy struggles to avoid recession, the outbreak has dealt another blow to confidence. Photo: Jin Yan)

The swordsmanship of the economic swordsman

My friend gave me a starbucks recharge card, and when she sent it out, starbucks was still where most Americans Punch in every day. By the time I received my friend's card, starbucks had closed more than 2,000 stores

At the beginning of the year, American industrial production stagnated. In late February, American consumer confidence was the single bright spot in the global economy. The list of US retailers now closed is long, with apple, Patagonia, Warby Parker, Urban Outfitters, Glossier and Allbirds, while Walmart and Lululemon restricted the opening hours.

Every year I feel the channel of spring. Besides the flowers and plants in early spring, the main way of the market is to see the people on the street, enjoying wine and chatting leisurely, or take the chairs and tables out on the street. The scene at noon on Saturday flashed briefly through some of Washington's neighborhoods and was blanketed in silence.

Virtually everything from cinemas and hotels to restaurants, bars, shops and beauty salons that can be seen on the streets has been hit.

U.S. stocks were even more breathtaking, falling by more than 2,000 points on March 9 and 12, with Dow Jones Industrial Average's fall touching a 7 percent primary market circuit breaker, the first time since 1997 that a circuit breaker has been triggered. The Dow Jones Industrial Average, Nasdaq composite and S & P 500 fell 27.76% , 26.64% and 26.74% , respectively, from February 20 to March 12 as U.S. stocks entered a technical bear market. As the US talk show star put it, investors saw the stock market was so bad that they screamed, "my money! "! Put his head in his hands, dare not see the market; and suddenly realized the spread of the epidemic, can not touch the face, and screaming "coronavirus" ! Quickly looked up, and then see the market fell again, and then screaming...

A lot of unseen risks are building up. The US is at the height of the financial cycle and the corporate sector faces huge debt risks. The risk of a global recession and a breakdown in OPEC negotiations have sent crude prices plummeting.

Under such difficult circumstances, it is time for the chairman of the Federal Reserve to step up to the plate. As one of the most powerful men in the world, the chairman of the Federal Reserve was called upon to maximize employment, stabilize prices, and communicate closely with the government. Many of my fellow economists have complained that the independence of the Fed chairman has been compromised in the Donald Trump era, but the new pneumonia epidemic is spreading around the world and growth is at risk, the only person who can take timely action to support economic stability and growth is the chairman of the Federal Reserve.

The financial bail-out fencer cut interest rates by 50 basis points on March 3rd, when he introduced his first set of swordplay. The market had expected another rate cut at the meeting on March 18, but Powell took the wind out of his sails and slashed the target range for the federal funds rate to 0-0.25 per cent. Such an intensive rate cut is rare in economic history. After the 2008 financial crisis, the Fed cut interest rates all the way to the ultra-low level of 0-0.25% to save the economy, followed by a seven-year policy of zero interest rates.

The Fed statement said the new crown disease has caused social and economic damage to many countries, including the United States. The global financial environment has been significantly affected. The rate cut will help support the U. S. economy, stabilize the job market, and maintain an inflation target.

In addition to the rate cut, the Fed announced a massive $700bn programme of quantitative easing, including buying back at least $500bn of treasury bonds and increasing its holdings of at least $200bn of mortgage-backed securities in a few months. The move is also unusual. After the 2008 financial crisis, the Fed launched at least three rounds of quantitative easing. The first round of quantitative easing, when the financial system was at its most critical, saw the Fed buy Fannie and Freddie debt and their mortgage-backed securities directly, bolstering the credit of financial institutions and stabilising markets in time.

Jeffrey Young, former global head of foreign exchange at Citigroup and co-founder and CEO of Deepmacro, explained to me that this could be an announcement effect.

The Three Musketeers together?

The so called announcement effect is the result of the swift passage of the pandemic relief bill in the House of Representatives after Donald Trump declared a state of emergency on Friday, coupled with the Fed's heavy hand, at least the combination of political and economic strength, in front of the virus to form a perfect combination of potential.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It's the ideal of fullness. In reality, the yield on the 10 year Treasury note fell 32 basis points after the Fed's rate cut, and Dow Jones Industrial Average and S & P 500 futures both fell sharply, melting down again.

As the Great Leader of the American people's fight against the plague, Donald Trump's main focus was containment. At the beginning of the outbreak, for example, he decided to ban Chinese flights to the United States and pushed for a travel ban, thinking that closing the border would solve the problem. The result is blindly defense, the virus step by step close.

In the United States, more than 1,300 cases were directly diagnosed and 36 deaths were recorded after the tactic of underplaying the scale of the crisis.

A lot of people asked me in mid-february how bad the epidemic would be in the United States. To answer this future-tense question, I looked at the US epidemic figures and replied that the US was not in serious trouble, that it would not exceed 1,500 in March -- I was going to say 1,200.

After Donald Trump drew criticism for his Buddhist swordplay, Donald Trump did not change his defensive style of play. "To prevent new cases from entering our country, " Donald Trump introduced travel restrictions for travellers from Europe. The United States Department of Homeland Security announced restrictions that would limit passengers returning from Europe to one of the 13 designated airports in the United States and require additional immigration checks, including answers about their health and travel history, and report personal information to the local health authorities.

President Donald Trump's announcement to ban most Europeans from entering the United States for the next 30 days is the most significant step he has taken so far against the new coronavirus, critics say. The move hastens his long-simmering separation from many of America's traditional allies.

Donald Trump said he would suspend travel between the United States and the 26 members of Europe's Schengen zone from midnight local time on the 13th. Later, Donald Trump included Britain and Ireland in Florida, allegedly without notice from the United States before he banned people from Europe from entering the United States.

The ultimatum first caused chaos at European airports, followed by designated "diversion" airports in Chicago, New York and Dallas. Hundreds of passengers returned from Europe on the evening of the 14th, according to one account, crowding the corridors. The border agents were caught off guard. Only a tenth of the border control windows are open to complaints from passengers, and some say they have been forced to wait more than six hours. In such a crowded environment, with passengers packed to the Gills, the airport does not take passengers'temperature or test them for the new coronavirus nucleic acid. The so-called "extra immigration check" simply requires answers about your health and travel history, and to follow CDC guidelines and Quarantine yourself when you get home. "It's like the end of the world. We'll all be infected in a week, " one passenger at the scene said gloomily

While the pairing remains to be seen, NIAID's highly respected director, Antony, who disagrees with Donald Trump, is a clear stream of communication outside the political realm. In an interview on Feb. 25, FAUCI warned that travel restrictions would become "irrelevant" if there was a new coronavirus pandemic, because "you can't shut the world out. ".

After Donald Trump said the US was "rapidly developing a new coronavirus vaccine" and "will basically vaccinate against it in a fairly rapid way" , FAUCI said, the process of developing a vaccine can take as long as a year to a year and a half.

Once, when I turned on the TV, DONALD TRUMP was talking about virus testing, and as usual, his language style was unacceptably plain, and he said, "test is beautiful, " which made me laugh. Here at Fossey, he said, the United States was "not really ready" to carry out the required new coronavirus test as the COVID-19 spread across the country. The United States can not process new coronavirus tests as quickly, easily or in equal numbers as other countries, even if the virus has spread to 44 states, which is a "failure. ".

He said the United States faces particular difficulties in testing for the virus. "The idea that anyone could easily do [ the test ] , what people in other countries and regions are doing, we're not ready for that. I think it should be done, but we're not, " Fossey said.

I couldn't laugh at anything Fossey said.

Fossey's sword is his expertise, and when asked about the length of time the new pneumonia outbreak in the United States has affected daily life, he said, it's hard to predict how long it will last, but historically it could last as long as eight weeks. On March 15th Fossey even raised the possibility of a full-blown US blockade. "Even in the face of criticism, " he said, "I would prefer a more radical approach. "
